Package controller

Class Inventory

java.lang.Object
controller.Inventory
All Implemented Interfaces:
javafx.fxml.Initializable
public class Inventory extends Object implements javafx.fxml.Initializable
The Inventory class is used to view and interact with the ObservableLists allParts and allProducts. Objects in allParts and allProducts can be added, deleted, and modified by the user.

    • lookupPart

      public static Part lookupPart(int partId)
      Returns a Part contained in allParts that matches the supplied partId integer argument. If no part is matched, the user is shown a warning that the part was not found and returns null.
      Returns:
      Part if a part is found, null if a match is not found.

    • lookupProduct

      public Product lookupProduct(int productId)
      Returns a Product contained in allProducts that matches the supplied productId integer argument. If no product is matched, the user is shown a warning that the product was not found and returns null.
      Returns:
      Product if a product is found, null if no match is found.

    • lookupPart

      public static javafx.collections.ObservableList<Part> lookupPart(String partName)
      Checks allParts for a partName that matches the Part.getName() and adds it to the partsByName list. If no Parts match, the original allParts list is returned and the user is notified that the searched part does not exist.
      Returns:
      ObservableList of Parts, or allParts if no matches are found.

    • lookupProduct

      public javafx.collections.ObservableList<Product> lookupProduct(String productName)
      Checks allProducts for a ProductName that matches the Product.getName() and adds it to the ProductsByName list. If no Products match, the original allProducts list is returned and the user is notified that the searched Product does not exist.
      Returns:
      ObservableList of Products, or allProducts if no matches are found.

    • partById

      public static javafx.collections.ObservableList<Part> partById(Part partToId)
      Checks allParts for a partId that matches the Part.getId() and adds it to the partsById list. If no Parts match, the original allParts list is returned.
      Parameters:
      partToId - The part to be searched by its ID.
      Returns:
      allParts as an ObservableList if it is not found, partById as an ObservableList if it is found.

    • productById

      public javafx.collections.ObservableList<Product> productById(Product productToId)
      Checks allProducts for a productId that matches the Product.getId() and adds it to the productsById list. If no Products match, the original allProducts list is returned.
      Parameters:
      productToId - The part to be searched by its ID.
      Returns:
      allProducts as an ObservableList if it is not found, productById as an ObservableList if it is found.

    • setSelectedPart

      public void setSelectedPart()
      Sets selectedProduct to null to ensure the user does not unintentionally delete or modify a product when they return to the ProductsTableView. Sets selectedPart to the Part in allParts that matches the part that the user clicks in the PartsTableView.

    • setSelectedProduct

      public void setSelectedProduct()
      Sets selectedPart to null to ensure the user does not unintentionally delete or modify a part when they return to the PartsTableView. Sets selectedProduct to the Product that the user clicks in the ProductsTableView.

    • intCheck

      public static boolean intCheck(String checkMe)
      Checks for a NumberFormatException to determine if the String argument is an integer. Returns true if an int can be parsed from the String argument. Returns false if the argument is null, or if a NumberFormatException occurs. "RUNTIME ERROR" Initially I ran into runtime errors in the Inventory GUI as I attempted to parse Strings for integers. When the Strings did not contain the correct type of data, I would run into a NumberFormatException. I created methods to catch these exceptions and return false to indicate the String did not contain an integer.
      Parameters:
      checkMe - The String to be checked.
      Returns:
      true if checkMe is an int, false if not.

    • doubleCheck

      public static boolean doubleCheck(String checkMe)
      Checks for a NumberFormatException to determine if the String argument is a double. Returns true if a double can be parsed from the String argument. Returns false if the argument is null, or if a NumberFormatException occurs. "RUNTIME ERROR" Initially I ran into runtime errors in the Inventory GUI as I attempted to parse Strings for doubles. When the Strings did not contain the correct type of data, I would run into a NumberFormatException. I created methods to catch these exceptions and return false to indicate the String did not contain a double.
      Parameters:
      checkMe - The String to be checked.
      Returns:
      true if checkMe is a double, false if not.

    • stringCheck

      public static boolean stringCheck(String checkMe)
      Runs isAlphabetic against the first character to determine if the String argument begins with an alphabetic character. Returns true if the String argument begins with an alphabetic character, returns false if the argument is null, an empty string, or begins with a non-alphabetic character.
      Parameters:
      checkMe - The String to be checked.
      Returns:
      true if checkMe begins with an alphabetic character, false if not.

    • onDeletePartButton

      public void onDeletePartButton(javafx.event.ActionEvent actionEvent)
      If selectedPart is not null an alert is displayed to the user. If the user clicks OK, deletePart() is called on the selectedPart, and selectedPart is set to null so it no longer stores a copy of the clicked part. If the user clicks CANCEL or closes the window, an info panel is displayed to the user to inform them the selectedPart has not been deleted. The selectedPart is then set to null. If the user has not selected a part, the user is warned they must select a part before attempting to delete it.

    • onDeleteProductButton

      public void onDeleteProductButton(javafx.event.ActionEvent actionEvent)
      If selectedProduct is not null an alert is displayed to the user. If the user clicks OK, deleteProduct() is called on the selectedProduct, and selectedProduct is set to null so it no longer stores a copy of the clicked Product. If the user clicks CANCEL or closes the window, an info panel is displayed to the user to inform them the selectedProduct has not been deleted. The selectedProduct is then set to null. If the user has not selected a Product, the user is warned they must select a Product before attempting to delete it.

    • onModifyPartButton

      public void onModifyPartButton(javafx.event.ActionEvent actionEvent) throws IOException
      Checks to see if the user has selected a part, then loads and displays the ModifyPart GUI if they have. If the user has not selected a part, they are warned to select a part before attempting to modify it.
      Throws:
      IOException

    • onModifyProductButton

      public void onModifyProductButton(javafx.event.ActionEvent actionEvent) throws IOException
      Checks to see if the user has selected a Product, then loads and displays the ModifyProduct GUI if they have. If the user has not selected a product, they are warned to select a product before attempting to modify it.
      Throws:
      IOException

    • onExitButton

      public void onExitButton(javafx.event.ActionEvent actionEvent)
      Calls System.exit() to exit the application

    • onSearchPartsTextField

      public void onSearchPartsTextField(javafx.scene.input.KeyEvent keyEvent)
      When the user presses enter after typing in the searchPartsTextField, or the searchPartsTextField is left empty the contents of the TextField are checked to determine if they are an integer or not. If the contents are an integer, the partsTableView is set to the results of partById search. If the contents are not an integer, the partsTableView is set to the results of a part name search.

    • onSearchProductsTextField

      public void onSearchProductsTextField(javafx.scene.input.KeyEvent keyEvent)
      When the user presses enter after typing in the searchProductsTextField, or the searchProductsTextField is left empty, the contents of the TextField are checked to determine if they are an integer or not. If the contents are an integer, the productsTableView is set to the results of productById search. If the contents are not an integer, the productsTableView is set to the results of a product name search.
